WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.760
I'm here to talk about enterprise-level data science success.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:14.600
It's making data science a success in a large company.

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:17.360
That's what I want to talk to you about.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:18.360
Who am I?

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:21.799
I've used R for about six years.

00:00:21.799 --> 00:00:24.840
I come from an engineering background.

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:30.040
In my professional role, I lead a data science, analytics, and software team in the supply

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:32.400
chain organization.

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:35.840
The silver lining of the last two years is I don't have to explain what supply chain

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:37.200
means to anybody.

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:43.439
From toilet paper to semiconductor chips, everybody understands what supply chain means.

00:00:43.439 --> 00:00:47.200
Flex is a large electronics manufacturing company.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:48.880
It's a Fortune 500 company.

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:50.759
It's located in 30 different countries.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:01:02.560
Outside of work, my primary role is a dad to two young kids, and mom currently thinks

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:08.160
I'm on vacation in a fancy conference resort.

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:10.860
The session was themed working with people is hard.

00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:13.199
It is hard.

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:19.599
I agree that it is not easy, but I'm here to try and convince you a little bit that

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:24.959
it need not be this hard.

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:29.080
So what does data science success in an enterprise mean?

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:36.440
I'm going to give you one definition that's my definition, where there is effort that

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:42.239
leads to some output, and then there are decisions made with that output, and actions and outcome

00:01:42.239 --> 00:01:46.720
for an organization or an enterprise.

00:01:46.839 --> 00:01:51.080
We know what the tools that we use in the effort and the outputs are.

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:52.879
We use R and Python.

00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:56.639
We publish our outputs.

00:01:56.639 --> 00:02:02.080
Now for the second part, decisions are generally made with other people in meetings, whether

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:08.880
it be with higher ups or your peers or with people who are the practitioners and users

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:12.720
of the output that we provide.

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:17.520
Decisions and outcomes typically mean we make more sales, we make more revenue.

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:23.800
The key performance indicators show improvement after implementing the analytics.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:30.639
My talk is going to be centered around the third and fourth phases of making data science

00:02:30.639 --> 00:02:38.839
success, and in most organizations, data science and analytics is a means to an end.

00:02:39.839 --> 00:02:46.080
Success is measured by dollars and metrics of what is important to the business, so it's

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:50.399
a means to an end in most cases.

00:02:50.399 --> 00:02:58.759
I see four sets as very fundamental to data science success in a corporation.

00:02:58.759 --> 00:03:04.880
It's the data set, the tool set, and the skill set is talked about a lot in this conference.

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:08.759
We have different tools that we have, we improve our skills.

00:03:08.759 --> 00:03:14.360
In this talk, I'm going to talk more on the mindset within an organization of how to take

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:22.000
it from development to deployment, where the first two boxes that you saw, implementation,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:30.119
actioning and outcome, is what the mindset change that is required for the last two processes.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:33.960
Partnership.

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:39.600
This is a word that means a lot, and I emphasize this within the organization.

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:44.039
There is a tendency to treat data science and IT organizations as a service provider

00:03:44.039 --> 00:03:47.399
within an organization.

00:03:47.399 --> 00:03:52.639
My passionate recommendation is do not settle for this.

00:03:53.639 --> 00:04:02.279
Ask to be equal partners, and what that means is the data science team gets equal input

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:07.559
to key decisions that are made with the analysis, that they get to offer opinion, they get to

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:15.080
guide the non-datas and the business people to execute on the output.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:21.279
In return, the data science team also owns the business outcome, so we take on an additional

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:30.320
challenge of owning business outcomes, and not just model deployment.

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:37.399
In terms of maturity of an organization to utilize and implement data science, I think

00:04:37.399 --> 00:04:39.600
of these as two-dimensional.

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:42.839
One is the analytics maturity or data science maturity.

00:04:42.839 --> 00:04:47.079
This could be ingesting large amounts of data, running complex models.

00:04:47.079 --> 00:04:50.720
The other important vector is decision maturity.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:56.359
Is the organization, how good is the data literacy of the organization?

00:04:56.359 --> 00:05:00.959
How good are they in decision making with the uncertain outputs that we have?

00:05:00.959 --> 00:05:07.239
Both of these vectors will have to grow for data science to be successful in an organization,

00:05:07.239 --> 00:05:17.480
they have to grow simultaneously, and both have to mature for it to be a success.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:25.079
Decision maturity is a fancy term for saying have a decision framework to utilize the output

00:05:25.079 --> 00:05:29.799
that is given from analytics.

00:05:29.799 --> 00:05:36.640
For the data science team, it is important to understand what are the key metrics that

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:43.160
are important for the practitioner of the analytics, or what's important for the business.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:48.359
And we talk a lot about model metrics, model accuracy, classification error, whatever the

00:05:48.359 --> 00:05:50.559
case might be.

00:05:50.559 --> 00:05:58.600
The model metrics only need to beat the current business process metric to be implementable.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:05:59.920
It's a two-horse race.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:05.600
A model accuracy does not need to be at 99% to be implemented if the business process

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:07.679
metric is today at 70%.

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:10.920
You don't have to beat the world record to beat the other horse, you just have to beat

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:12.200
the other horse.

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:19.040
And then make decisions to implement the data science side of things on the business side

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:23.239
of things.

00:06:23.239 --> 00:06:29.000
This is contradictory to, you know, working nicely with people.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:34.959
It's important to pick some fights, and you have to fight for the right reasons.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.480
Friction is a very necessary component to moving forward.

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:40.399
Good friction is good.

00:06:40.399 --> 00:06:46.320
That removes hurdles and blockades that sometimes come when different teams have to work together

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:51.799
to move things forward.

00:06:51.799 --> 00:06:56.600
I want to make an illustration or an example of how do we go from model output to decision

00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:57.600
making.

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:04.559
You see a picture of Google Maps that takes us from where we are today to Dulles Airport.

00:07:04.559 --> 00:07:07.959
Many of us will be making this trip in the next 24 hours.

00:07:07.959 --> 00:07:12.760
Google Maps tells me it's going to take 45 minutes.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:15.920
I ask the question to Google Maps, how long is it going to take?

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:18.519
But that's not the real question.

00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:23.160
When I have to make a decision with the answer it's given me, the decision making breaks

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:28.720
down into multiple tree-type decision making.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:32.959
Do I want to take Uber or can I afford to take public transportation?

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:34.920
Do I have time for coffee?

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:40.440
When you put this decision making framework on top of the very complex analytics that's

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:47.320
running behind Google Maps, that gives you a framework to connect data science to business-type

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:48.320
decision making.

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:53.040
Talk to your stakeholders to understand what decisions do they really want to make with

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:56.140
the data output.

00:07:56.140 --> 00:08:02.839
Going from a generic example, I'll go to a supply chain and a specific example.

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:07.839
Within the supply chain organization, we have analytics that support, that provide output

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:10.119
for what the price of a part should be.

00:08:10.119 --> 00:08:16.000
My organization and company buy millions of parts every year.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.440
You can see the scale of the pricing.

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:25.839
When we provide some model outputs that show lower than current price, the person who has

00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:30.880
to execute on it, when they first see it, they get some pressure.

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:34.599
They get some pressure or fear that they have to go meet that target.

00:08:34.599 --> 00:08:42.679
The pressure or fear is not within that one person's scope, but their manager also sees

00:08:42.679 --> 00:08:43.679
this data.

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:46.080
That's where the pressure comes from.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:51.960
There is a very high chance that giving analytics in an organization can create some pressure

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:53.799
or fear.

00:08:53.799 --> 00:08:59.799
However, if the person were to achieve any lower price for that part, whether it meets

00:08:59.799 --> 00:09:05.359
the target, regardless of whether it meets the target or not, that's an opportunity.

00:09:05.359 --> 00:09:11.280
It is very important to work within an organization to change people's perception of analytics

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:17.039
from feeling pressure or fear to creating that opportunity and growth mindset.

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:22.479
We call it the pressure to opportunity mindset change, and it takes time when you work with

00:09:22.479 --> 00:09:28.359
different teams.

00:09:28.359 --> 00:09:31.400
Analytics tend to judge machines and models very harshly.

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:36.039
I'll give two scenarios with this exact case of pricing a part.

00:09:36.039 --> 00:09:43.640
Now, let's take the case of the part was a dollar and the model output was 90 cents,

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:48.280
and the actual achievement after the negotiation was 95 cents.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:54.239
In case one, or scenario one, with a model, people tend to judge the model and say the

00:09:54.239 --> 00:09:57.960
model has 50% error.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:03.400
In case number two, or scenario two, without a machine or a model, and when a human went

00:10:03.400 --> 00:10:09.039
in with a low bid as a starting point, and they started with 90 cents and got up to 95

00:10:09.039 --> 00:10:12.320
cents as the result, it was a good negotiating strategy.

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:16.880
So humans tend to judge machines and models in a very harsh way.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:19.919
We have a lot of empathy towards other humans.

00:10:19.919 --> 00:10:28.640
So what we have learned in doing analytics at scale within a large company is be aware

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:35.400
of being judged in a very harsh way and prepare for that.

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:43.320
So with people, there's building relationships with people up, down, and sideways, up the

00:10:43.320 --> 00:10:50.039
management chain with your teams and your peers.

00:10:50.039 --> 00:10:55.239
The data science and analytics team, to be successful, have to learn to understand and

00:10:55.239 --> 00:10:58.559
talk the language of the business teams.

00:10:58.559 --> 00:11:08.119
When we say models and random forest and regression, everybody does not understand those terms.

00:11:08.119 --> 00:11:11.719
It makes them a little closed and feared.

00:11:11.719 --> 00:11:16.719
So we have to open up and learn to talk their language to get how they can execute and do

00:11:16.719 --> 00:11:20.840
their jobs better with what we are giving them.

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:24.119
And building a successful team takes time.

00:11:24.119 --> 00:11:30.479
Manage, lead, and coach are three different things, and all three have to be done in a

00:11:30.479 --> 00:11:32.479
different way.

00:11:32.479 --> 00:11:40.239
And similarly, as we challenge the non-datas to speak our language, we have to challenge

00:11:40.239 --> 00:11:49.280
the data science team in an organization to speak the business team's language.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:57.799
Some pitfalls that I've learned over time, when management asks for machine learning,

00:11:57.799 --> 00:12:01.919
whenever they start a question is, let's see if AI ML can help here.

00:12:01.919 --> 00:12:05.179
That's usually a rabbit hole.

00:12:05.179 --> 00:12:07.719
Can we find something interesting from the data?

00:12:07.719 --> 00:12:10.760
That's another big rabbit hole.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:14.320
Be aware of scope creep in an organization.

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:25.760
Have a clear plan and a threshold for aborting a project with your project stakeholders.

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:29.200
So working with people need not be this hard.

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:34.799
Working with people is a very necessary component of enterprise-level data success.

00:12:35.799 --> 00:12:37.799
So, thank you.

00:12:37.799 --> 00:12:39.799
APPLAUSE

